{
  "texts": [
    "In this rapidly expanding literature, we aim to contribute to the debates on the ability of LLMs to replace human subjects, in two ways.",
    "First, given the centrality of the discussion about algorithmic biases, we suggest a systematic approach that helps to determine their presence in the responses of LLMs when prompted to imitate the views of diverse groups, and propose an operationalization of the notion of social bias.",
    "Second, our article offers a new take in the debate between representativity vs. bias of LLMs.",
    "We build on an emerging literature showing that LLMs are either brittle (Plaza-del Arco et al., 2024; Wang et al., 2024b; Barrie et al., 2024; Berglund et al., 2024), not appropriate for closed-form answering (Röttger et al., 2024), or that they do not necessarily exhibit a consistent social bias.",
    "Other articles also exhibit results in the models that cannot be linked to any subsample of the population, although they do so mostly incidentally."
  ]
}